    <p>For conversions beyond this table, simply multiply the number of ounces by 28.3495. For example, 24 ounces equals 24 times 28.3495, which is 680.4 grams. Use our <a href="/unit-converter/">unit converter</a> for instant conversions between any weight units.</p>

    <h2>Troy Ounce vs. Avoirdupois Ounce</h2>
    <p>One of the most common sources of confusion in weight measurement is the existence of two different types of ounces. Understanding when each applies is crucial for accurate conversions.</p>

    <h3>The Avoirdupois Ounce (Standard Ounce)</h3>
    <p>The avoirdupois system is the standard weight measurement system used in the United States and for most purposes in the United Kingdom. The word "avoirdupois" comes from the Old French "aveir de peis," meaning "goods of weight." In this system:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>1 ounce = 28.3495 grams</li>
      <li>16 ounces = 1 pound</li>
      <li>1 pound = 453.592 grams</li>
      <li>2,000 pounds = 1 short ton</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This is the ounce you encounter in grocery stores, on nutrition labels, at the post office, and in everyday life. When someone says "ounce" without any qualifier, they almost always mean the avoirdupois ounce.</p>

    <h3>The Troy Ounce (Precious Metals)</h3>
    <p>The troy ounce is used exclusively for measuring precious metals — gold, silver, platinum, and palladium. The troy system is named after Troyes, France, a medieval trading center where this measurement standard was widely used. In the troy system:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>1 troy ounce = 31.1035 grams</li>
      <li>12 troy ounces = 1 troy pound</li>
      <li>1 troy pound = 373.242 grams</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Note that a troy pound has only 12 ounces (not 16), and each troy ounce is heavier than a regular ounce. This means a troy pound (373.2 g) is actually lighter than a regular pound (453.6 g), even though each individual troy ounce is heavier. This can be confusing, which is why precious metals are almost always quoted in troy ounces, never troy pounds.</p>

