    <p>When you see gold priced at "1,900 per ounce," that refers to a troy ounce (31.1 grams), not a standard ounce (28.3 grams). This distinction matters — confusing the two would mean a 9.7 percent error in your calculations.</p>

    <h2>Ounces to Grams in Cooking and Baking</h2>
    <p>Cooking and baking are the most common everyday contexts where ounce-to-gram conversions are needed. This is especially true when following recipes from different countries, since most of the world uses the metric system.</p>

    <h3>Why Grams Are Better for Baking</h3>
    <p>Professional bakers overwhelmingly prefer measuring ingredients by weight in grams rather than by volume in cups. The reason is precision: a cup of flour can weigh anywhere from 120 to 160 grams depending on how it is scooped, whether it is sifted, humidity, and the type of flour. By contrast, 150 grams of flour is always 150 grams of flour, regardless of how you scoop it into the bowl. For delicate baked goods where ingredient ratios are critical — such as macarons, souffles, and pastry — weighing in grams is the difference between success and failure.</p>

