    <h2>Fluid Ounces vs. Weight Ounces: A Critical Distinction</h2>
    <p>One of the most common measurement mistakes is confusing fluid ounces (a unit of volume) with ounces (a unit of weight). These are completely different measurements that happen to share a name.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Ounce (oz):</strong> A unit of weight equal to 28.3495 grams. Measures how heavy something is.</li>
      <li><strong>Fluid ounce (fl oz):</strong> A unit of volume equal to approximately 29.574 milliliters (US) or 28.413 milliliters (Imperial). Measures how much space a liquid occupies.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For water, 1 fluid ounce weighs very close to 1 ounce (since water's density is approximately 1 g/mL), which is the historical reason the two units share a name. But for other substances, the weight and volume ounces can differ dramatically. For example, 1 fluid ounce of honey weighs about 1.5 ounces because honey is denser than water. And 1 fluid ounce of cooking oil weighs about 0.95 ounces because oil is less dense than water.</p>
    <p>In cooking, this distinction matters most with dense liquids (honey, molasses, corn syrup) and light dry ingredients (flour, cocoa powder). When a recipe specifies "ounces," look for context clues — dry ingredients are typically measured by weight, while liquids are measured by volume.</p>

